review_comments.body:
nit: I consider this lambda-style pattern to be most readable if you logically think of this expression as a function definition.  In that way, it would read:

``` java
public void enable() { ... }

private void enableOnUiThread() { ... }

private final Runnable mEnableRunnable = () -> {
  // code here...
};
```

Yes it technically violates that member variables go up top, but the pattern really is about a defining a function and referring to it as a pointer.  In C/C++, for instance, do exactly that making it really unintuitive for you to declare the method inside a function body as a nested function.

